All four of your scenarios hit documented .NET 11 breaking changes:

---

### 1. GZipStream empty output detection — **BREAKS** 
([dotnet/docs#49393](https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/49393))

In .NET 11, `GZipStream` (and `DeflateStream`) **always writes headers/footers**, even when no data is written. Your zero-byte check will never trigger — the output will always contain bytes.

**Fix:** Check the *decompressed* length or track whether you wrote data yourself:
```csharp
bool wroteData = false;
// ... write to gzipStream, set wroteData = true ...
// Instead of: if (outputStream.Length == 0)
if (!wroteData) { /* no data scenario */ }
```

---

### 2. TarReader with invalid checksums — **BREAKS**
([dotnet/docs#49394](https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/49394))

`TarReader` now **validates checksums** and throws `InvalidDataException` for mismatches. Legacy hand-crafted TARs with bad checksums will fail.

**Fix:** Catch `InvalidDataException` around `GetNextEntry()`:
```csharp
try {
    while (reader.GetNextEntry() is { } entry) { /* ... */ }
} catch (InvalidDataException ex) {
    // Handle corrupt/legacy TAR
}
```

---

### 3. ZipArchive.CreateAsync eager loading — **BREAKS**
([dotnet/docs#50254](https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/50254))

`CreateAsync` now **eagerly reads the central directory** (async). Exceptions from malformed entries now surface at `CreateAsync` instead of when accessing `.Entries`. If you relied on lazy loading (e.g., deferred error handling), move exception handling to the `CreateAsync` call:

```csharp
try {
    var archive = await ZipArchive.CreateAsync(stream, ZipArchiveMode.Read);
} catch (InvalidDataException ex) {
    // Was previously thrown at .Entries access
}
```

---

### 4. MemoryStream max capacity — **BREAKS**
([dotnet/docs#49545](https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/49545))

Max capacity is reduced from `int.MaxValue` (`0x7FFFFFFF`) to **`0x7FFFFFC7`** (`Array.MaxLength`). The exception also changes from `OutOfMemoryException` to `ArgumentOutOfRangeException`.

**Fix:** Cap allocations at `Array.MaxLength` and update catch blocks:
```csharp
const int MaxCap = 0x7FFFFFC7; // Array.MaxLength
// Update exception handling:
catch (ArgumentOutOfRangeException) { /* was OutOfMemoryException */ }
```
